Import CSV file copied from ESPN Player Data

setwd("/Users/jcorritone/Desktop/Fantasy Efficacy Score/week-one")
espn_week_one_data = read_csv("espn-week-one-data.csv")
## Rows: 356 Columns: 16
##  Column specification 
## Delimiter: ","
## chr (16): player_name, team, position, type, blank, opp, status, proj, point...
## 
##  Use `spec()` to retrieve the full column specification for this data.
##  Specify the column types or set `show_col_types = FALSE` to quiet this message.
# The CSV contains unnecessary header rows. Remove them here:
espn_week_one_data = espn_week_one_data[-c(51, 102, 153, 204, 255, 306), ]

# The CSV contains many columns that contain irrelevant information to the FES calculation. To keep only necessary columns:
cleaned_espn_week_one_data = espn_week_one_data %>%
  select(player_name, team, position, proj, points, start_percent)

# Because ESPN data shows start_percent on a scale from 0-100, we must change the scale to proportion from 0-1. In addition, ensure the points column is treated as a numeric:
cleaned_espn_week_one_data = cleaned_espn_week_one_data %>%
  mutate(start_percent = as.numeric(start_percent) / 100) %>%
  mutate(points = as.numeric(points))

# Remove players with 0 projected points to maintain realism and account for injured players. In addition, remove players that were started in 0% of leagues
cleaned_espn_week_one_data = cleaned_espn_week_one_data %>%
  mutate(proj = ifelse(proj == "--", 0, proj),
         proj = as.numeric(proj)) %>%
  filter(proj != 0) %>%
  filter(start_percent != 0.000)

# Export the cleaned_espn_week_X_data as a CSV
write.csv(cleaned_espn_week_one_data, 
          "/Users/jcorritone/Desktop/cleaned_espn_week_one_data.csv", 
          row.names = FALSE)

Using the cleaned data, calculate the baseline (expected weekly output for a starting caliber player) for each position. Note that the baseline will be different week to week AND position to position.

Once the baseline value for each position is calculated, a new column is created containing this value, matched to each player by their position.

Using the FES formula, one more column is added to represent the FES of each player.

week_one_baselines = cleaned_espn_week_one_data %>%
    group_by(position) %>%
    summarise(baseline = sum(points * start_percent, na.rm = TRUE) / sum(start_percent, na.rm = TRUE),
              .groups = "drop")

fes_week_one_data = cleaned_espn_week_one_data %>%
  left_join(week_one_baselines, by = "position") %>%
  mutate(fes = (points - baseline) * start_percent)

write.csv(fes_week_one_data, 
          "/Users/jcorritone/Desktop/fes_week_one_data.csv", 
          row.names = FALSE)

Visualize FES output for each position by creating a histogram revealing the FES distribution

# The following distributions show graphs only including players started in over 10% of ESPN fantasy leagues to remove bench player noise.

# Histogram of FES
ggplot(fes_week_one_data %>% filter(start_percent > .10), aes(x = fes)) +
  geom_histogram(bins = 20, fill = "steelblue", color = "black") +
  labs(title = "Histogram of FES (Week 1)", subtitle = "Players Started in Greater Than 10% of ESPN Leagues", x = "FES", y = "Number of Players") +
  theme_linedraw()

# Scatter Plot of Fantasy Points & FES
ggplot(fes_week_one_data %>% filter(start_percent > .10), aes(x = points, y = fes)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, ) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, color = "darkred", alpha = 0.6) +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of FES & Fantasy Points (Week 1)", subtitle = "Players Started in Greater Than 10% of ESPN Leagues", x = "Fantasy Points", y = "FES") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 10, )
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

# Box Plot of FES Across Positions
ggplot(fes_week_one_data %>% filter(start_percent > .10), aes(x = position, y = fes, fill = position)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  labs(title = "Box Plot of FES Across Positions (Week 1)", subtitle = "Players Started in Greater Than 10% of ESPN Leagues", x = "Player Position", y = "FES") +
  theme_linedraw()

# Scatter Plot of Start Percent & FES
ggplot(fes_week_one_data, aes(x = start_percent, y = fes)) +
  geom_point(alpha = 0.6, ) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = F, color = "darkgreen", alpha = 0.6) +
  theme_linedraw()
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

fes_week_one_data <- fes_week_one_data %>%
  mutate(highlight = ifelse(player_name %in% c("Josh Allen", "Derrick Henry", "Joe Burrow", "Justin Fields", "Broncos D/ST"), "Highlight", "Normal"))

# Scatter Plot with highlighted points
library(ggrepel)

ggplot(fes_week_one_data %>% filter(start_percent > 0.10), 
       aes(x = points, y = fes)) +
  geom_point(aes(color = highlight), alpha = 0.7) +  # map color to highlight
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE, color = "darkred")  +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("Highlight" = "navy")) +  # choose colors
  geom_text_repel(
    data = subset(fes_week_one_data, player_name %in% c("Josh Allen", "Derrick Henry", "Joe Burrow", "Justin Fields", "Broncos D/ST")),
    aes(label = player_name),
    size = 2,
    nudge_y = -0.75,          # adjust vertical position of labels
    color = "navy",
    fontface = "bold"
  ) +
  labs(title = "Scatter Plot of FES & Fantasy Points (Week 1)",
       subtitle = "Players Started in Greater Than 10% of ESPN Leagues",
       x = "Fantasy Points",
       y = "FES") +
  theme_bw(base_size = 10)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
